<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-147-284  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 147 284.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics Weekly  Feb 7 1990 n1494 p26(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Theft: industry pays up.(includes related article detailing a caseof computer fraud and on detailing employee theft)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bennett, Chris.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A survey by the London Business School estimates the annual costof corporate crime at 1.5 billion pounds sterling, but this isconsidered to be a gross underestimate because no one wants toadmit corporate crime exists.andP;  Companies write off losses ratherthan invest in security measures, largely because no one wants toadmit that corporate crime happened to them.andP;  Corporate crimefalls mainly into one of three subgroups: computer fraud, employeetheft and industrial espionage.andP;  Computer fraud can be made moredifficult by the use and frequent changing of passwords, and bycontrolling physical access to computers and back-up units.andO;Employee crime covers a wide range of activities from minorpilfering to major theft, and should be dealt with according tothe seriousness of the offense in order to avoid creatingunnecessary anxiety among the workforce.andP;  Industrial espionageinvolves devices ranging in cost from five to 1,500 pounds, putequipment is also available to detect such bugs.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer CrimesComputer HackersCompaniesTheft of FundsTheft of InformationSecurityComputer Industry.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>